window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"You are provided with a uniform metre rule of mass,  M  indicated on its reverse side, a knife edge, a graduated measuring cylinder of known mass,  m1  marked on it, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Read and record the values of  M  and  m1 .  (ii) Balance the metre rule horizontally on the knife edge. Read and record the balance point as G.  (iii) Tie a loop of thread around the neck of the measuring cylinder.  (iv) Fill the cylinder with the sand provided to the 2 cm-3 mark. Record the volume,  V, of the sand.  (v) Hang the cylinder at the 2 cm mark of the metre rule and adjust the position of the knife edge until the rule balances horizontally.  (vi) Read and record the new balance position  K .  (vii) Determine the value of  e and  f .  (viii) Determine the mass, m2\u200b, of the sand in the measuring cylinder. Hint: m2 = m\u00d7fe\\frac{m\u00d7f}{e}em\u00d7f\u200b -  m1   (ix) Repeat the procedure by filling the measuring cylinder to the mark V = 4, 6, 8 and 10 cm3. In each case, ensure that the measuring cylinder is kept constant at the 2 cm mark on the metre rule.  (x) Tabulate your readings.  (xi) Plot a graph with  m2 on the vertical axis and  V  on the horizontal axis.  (xii) Determine the slope,  s, of the graph.  (xiii) State  two  precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    V(cm3)K(cm)e = (K - P)(cm)f = G - K(cm)m2 = mfe\\frac{mf}{e}emf\u200b - m1 (g)243.541.56.91.614442.740.77.73.443641.939.98.56.372841.139.19.39.4161040.438.410.012.178        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 12\u22121.87510\u22122.5\\frac{12-1.875}{10-2.5}10\u22122.512\u22121.875\u200b= 10.1257.5\\frac{10.125}{7.5}7.510.125\u200b = 1.35 g/cm3    Precautions:  1. I ensured there was no draught to prevent interference with the setup and maintain stable readings.    2. I avoided parallax error by positioning my eye level directly with the markings on the meter rule.    3. I kept the measuring cylinder suspended, ensuring it did not rest on or touch the table to avoid inaccurate readings.    4. I firmly secured the knife edge to maintain its position and prevent any movement during the experiment.    5. I repeated all measurements to enhance accuracy and reduce random errors in the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"Determine the mass of 7.5 cm3 of the sand using your graph. [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p and with the unit e.g 123.123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"For a volume of 7.5 cm3, the corresponding mass, as accurately determined from the graph, is m2 = 8.625 g.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"FLUID AT REST : VOLUME, DENSITY AND RELATIVE DENSITY","question":"A gold coin of mass 102.0 g has uniform cross-sectional area of 10.0 cm2.  Calculate its thickness. (Density of gold = 19.3 gcm-3). [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p and with the unit e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"V = massdensityV = \\frac{mass}{density}V = densitymass\u200b = 10219.3\\frac{102}{19.3}19.3102\u200b = 5.28 cm3    volume = thickness \u00d7 area    \u2234 thickness = volumearea\\frac{volume}{area}areavolume\u200b = 5.2810\\frac{5.28}{10}105.28\u200b = 0.53 cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Using the diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions:    (i) Fix a plane sheet of paper on the cellotex board.  (ii) Place the rectangular glass prism on the paper and trace its outline,  ABCD . Remove the prism.  (iii) Draw a normal  NMP  to meet  AB  and  DC  at M and P respectively such that  \u2223AM\u2223=\u2223DP\u2223  = 2.0 cm.  (iv) Trace the ray  PQ  with two pins,  P1 and  P2  at P and Q respectively such that angle MPQ = i = 5\u00b0.  (v) Replace the prism on its outline. Trace the emergent ray with two other pins  P3  and  P4 such that they lie in a straight line with  P2 and the image of  P1  viewed through the glass prism.  (vi) Measure and record \u03b8, the angle between the emergent ray and face  AB  of the glass prism.  (vii) Evaluate cos \u03b8 and sin i.  (viii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of i = 10\u00b0, 15\u00b0, 20\u00b0 and 25\u00b0.  (ix) Tabulate your readings.  (x) Plot a graph with cos \u03b8 on the vertical axis and sin i on the horizontal axis.  (xi) Determine the slope,  s, of the graph.  (xii) State  two  precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    io\u03b8ocos \u03b8sin i5.083.00.1370.08710.074.00.2760.17415.065.00.4230.25920.065.00.5590.34225.048.00.6690.423        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.6\u22120.20.375\u22120.125\\frac{0.6-0.2}{0.375-0.125}0.375\u22120.1250.6\u22120.2\u200b = 0.40.25\\frac{0.4}{0.25}0.250.4\u200b = 1.6    Precautions:  1. I ensured that all pins were placed vertically and securely to maintain accuracy.    2. I avoided parallax error by positioning my eye level directly with the markings on the meter rule.    3. I made sure that the pins were spaced at a reasonable distance to allow clear tracing of lines.    4. I avoided parallax error when reading measurements from the protractor by aligning my eye directly with the angle markings.    5. I checked that the ruler and protractor were clean and free of obstructions to enhance visibility and accuracy in measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the laws of refraction of light. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. The incident ray, the refracted ray, and the normal at the point of incidence are all in the same plane. This means that the light rays and the normal line lie in a single flat surface. \u00a0     2. The ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for any two given media. This constant is known as the refractive index. Mathematically, it can be expressed as:    n = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(r)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(r\\right)}}sin(r)sin(i)\u200b","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Explain what is meant by the statement: the refractive index of a material is 1.65. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The statement \"the refractive index of a material is 1.65\" means that light travels 1.65 times slower in that material compared to how it travels in a vacuum. In other words, the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to the speed of light in the material is 1.65. The refractive index (n) quantifies how much the light ray bends when it enters the material from another medium, such as air. A higher refractive index indicates a greater reduction in the speed of light and more bending.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a constantan wire, a 2 \u03a9 standard resistor, an accumulator E, an ammeter  A , a key K and necessary apparatus.    (i) Measure and record the emf of the accumulator provided.  (ii) Connect a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (iii) Close the key, read and record the ammeter reading  Io  when the crocodile clip is  not  in contact with the constantan wire.  (iv) Open the key with the clip making contact with the wire, when  d  = 90 cm, close the key. Read and record the ammeter reading I.  (v) Evaluate  d-1.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of d = 80, 70, 60 and 50 cm.  (vi) In each case, read and record the ammeter reading and evaluate  d-1.   (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with  I  on the vertical axis and  d-1 on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope,  s, of the graph and its intercept,  c, on the vertical axis.  (xii) Evaluate k = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b  (xiii) Using your graph, determine the current I when d = 55 cm.  (xiii) State  two  precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Io = 0.06 A    Table of values / observation  d(cm)I(A)d-1(cm-1)80.00.230.01370.00.250.01460.00.310.01750.00.340.02040.00.390.025        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.375\u22120.150.0231\u22120.0062\\frac{0.375-0.15}{0.0231-0.0062}0.0231\u22120.00620.375\u22120.15\u200b = 0.2250.0169\\frac{0.225}{0.0169}0.01690.225\u200b = 13.31 A/cm-1    Intercept, c on the vertical axis = 0.07 A    k = cs\\frac{c}{s}sc\u200b = 0.0713.31\\frac{0.07}{13.31}13.310.07\u200b = 0.00526 cm-1    when d = 55 cm,  I = 0.31 A    Precautions:  1. I ensured that parallax error was avoided when reading the ammeter by positioning my eye directly in line with the scale markings.    2. I removed the key from the circuit whenever readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary drainage of the battery.    3. I verified that all connections were tight and secure to minimize resistance and ensure accurate current readings.    4. I inspected the ammeter for any signs of damage or malfunction before use to guarantee reliable measurements.    5. I calibrated the ammeter prior to starting the experiment to confirm accuracy in the current readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Explain what is meant by the potential difference between two points in an electric circuit. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit is the amount of energy required to move a unit charge from one point to the other. It represents the work done per unit charge as it moves through the circuit, effectively driving the electric current between these points. Potential difference is measured in volts (V).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2013>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2013","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"State two factors on which the resistance of a wire depends. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Length of the Wire: Resistance increases with the length of the wire; a longer wire has higher resistance.  2. Cross-sectional Area: Resistance decreases as the cross-sectional area increases; a thicker wire has lower resistance.  3. Material of the Wire: Different materials have different resistivities; for example, copper has lower resistance compared to iron for the same length and thickness.  4. Temperature: Resistance generally increases with temperature, as higher temperatures cause more atomic vibrations, which impede the flow of electrons.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];